   Schutte   ‘archer’.","English: nickname for a short person, from Middle English <i>scut(e)</i> ‘short’, or else for a swift runner, from Middle English <i>scut</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Henry Scott - Third Lord of Balweary was born in 1275, in Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland, his father, Sir Michael Scott Second Lord of Balwearie, was 26 and his mother, Lady Margaret Balweary, was 40. He married Mrs. Henry Scott in 1300, in Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1330, in his hometown, at the age of 55, and was buried in Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1275–1330":"1275–1330","1265–1294":"1265–1294","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","1279–Female":"1279–Surnud","1315–1355":"1315–1355","1249–1304":"1249–1304","1235–Female":"1235–Surnud","1304":"1304","1315":"1315","1249":"1249","1235":"1235","1279":"1279","1268":"1268","1300":"1300","1355":"1355","1265":"1265","1275":"1275","1330":"1330","1294":"1294","Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland","Balwearie Castle, Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1275–1330":"1275–1330","1265–1294":"1265–1294","1268–Male":"1268–Kuollut","1279–Female":"1279–Kuollut","1315–1355":"1315–1355","1249–1304":"1249–1304","1235–Female":"1235–Kuollut","1304":"1304","1315":"1315","1249":"1249","1235":"1235","1279":"1279"